WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:17.300
Chapter 1 of Meditations of Marcus Aurelius The Meditations of Marcus Aurelius by Marcus

00:17.300 --> 00:21.080
Aurelius Antoninus Translated by George Long

00:21.080 --> 00:22.960
CHAPTER 1

00:24.020 --> 00:29.460
1. For my grandfather Verus, I learned good morals and the government of my temper.

00:30.580 --> 00:35.960
2. From the reputation and remembrance of my father, modesty and a manly character.

00:37.000 --> 00:42.660
3. For my mother, piety and beneficence and abstinence, not only from evil deeds,

00:42.960 --> 00:46.840
but even from evil thoughts, and further simplicity in my way of living,

00:47.120 --> 00:52.260
far removed from the habits of the rich. 4. For my great grandfather,

00:52.260 --> 00:56.520
not to have frequented public schools, and to have had good teachers at home,

00:56.740 --> 01:00.280
and to know that on such things a man should spend liberally.

01:01.220 --> 01:06.280
5. For my governor, to be neither of the green nor of the blue party at the games in the circus,

01:06.680 --> 01:11.640
nor partisan either of the Parmularius or the Scutarius at the gladiator's fights.

01:12.180 --> 01:17.220
From him too I learned endurance of labor, and to want little and to work with my own hands,

01:17.480 --> 01:21.680
and not to meddle with other people's affairs, and not to be ready to listen to slander.

01:22.980 --> 01:29.000
6. From Diognatus, not to busy myself about trifling things, and not to give credit to what

01:29.000 --> 01:34.360
was said by miracle-workers and jugglers about incantations and the driving away of demons

01:34.360 --> 01:39.880
and such things, and not to breed quails for fighting, nor to give myself up passionately

01:39.880 --> 01:45.340
to such things, and to endure freedom of speech, and to have become intimate with philosophy,

01:45.920 --> 01:50.540
and to have been a hearer first of Bacchaeus, then of Tandassus and Marcianus,

01:50.540 --> 01:55.560
and to have written dialogues in my youth, and to have desired a plank, bed and skin,

01:55.960 --> 01:58.700
and whatever else of the kind belongs to the Grecian discipline.

01:59.940 --> 02:03.880
7. From Rusticus I received the impression that my character required improvement

02:03.880 --> 02:09.180
and discipline, and from him I learned not to be led astray to sophisticated emulation,

02:09.500 --> 02:14.360
nor to writing on speculative matters, nor to delivering little oratory orations,

02:14.760 --> 02:18.020
nor to showing myself off as a man who practices much discipline,

02:18.020 --> 02:22.700
or does benevolent acts in order to make a display, and to abstain from rhetoric,

02:23.060 --> 02:27.920
and poetry, and fine writing, and not to walk about in the house in my outdoor dress,

02:28.340 --> 02:32.160
nor to do other things of the kind, and to write my letters with simplicity,

02:32.600 --> 02:37.940
like the letter which Rusticus wrote from Senuisa to my mother, and with respect to those who have

02:37.940 --> 02:43.920
offended me by words or done me wrong, to be easily disposed to be pacified and reconciled

02:43.920 --> 02:48.100
as soon as they have shown a readiness to be reconciled, and to read carefully,

02:48.340 --> 02:53.040
and not to be satisfied with the superficial understanding of a book, nor hastily to give

02:53.040 --> 02:58.120
my assent to those who talk over much, and I am indebted to him for being acquainted with the

02:58.120 --> 03:02.400
discourses of Epictetus which he communicated to me out of his own collection.

03:03.840 --> 03:09.140
8. From Apollonius I learned freedom of will and undeviating steadiness of purpose,

03:09.140 --> 03:14.820
and to look to nothing else, not even for a moment, except to reason, and to be always the

03:14.820 --> 03:20.920
same in sharp pains, on the occasion of the loss of a child, and in long illness, and to see clearly

03:20.920 --> 03:26.640
in a living example that the same man can be both most resolute and yielding, and not peevish in

03:26.640 --> 03:31.760
giving his instruction, and to have had before my eyes a man who clearly considered his experience

03:31.760 --> 03:36.300
and his skill in expounding philosophical principles as the smallest of his merits.

03:36.300 --> 03:40.900
And from him I learned how to receive from friends what are esteemed favours

03:40.900 --> 03:44.920
without being either humbled by them or letting them pass unnoticed.

03:46.260 --> 03:51.960
From Sextus a benevolent disposition, and the example of a family governed in a fatherly manner,

03:52.460 --> 03:58.480
and the idea of living conformably to nature, and gravity without effectation, and to look carefully

03:58.480 --> 04:03.400
after the interests of friends, and to tolerate ignorant persons, and those who form opinions

04:03.400 --> 04:09.200
without consideration. He had the power of readily accommodating himself to all, so that intercourse

04:09.200 --> 04:14.460
with him was more agreeable than any flattery, and at the same time he was most highly venerated by

04:14.460 --> 04:19.940
those who associated with him, and he had the faculty both of discovering and ordering in an

04:19.940 --> 04:25.200
intelligent and methodical way the principles necessary for life, and he never showed anger

04:25.200 --> 04:31.100
or any other passion, but was entirely free from passion, and also most affectionate, and he could

04:31.100 --> 04:36.780
express approbation without noisy display, and he possessed much knowledge without ostentation.

04:38.520 --> 04:44.440
From Alexander, the grammarian, to refrain from fault-finding, and not in a reproachful way to

04:44.440 --> 04:50.420
chide those who uttered any barbarous or soloistic or strange-sounding expression, but dexterously

04:50.420 --> 04:55.340
to introduce the very expression which ought to have been used, and in the way of answer or giving

04:55.340 --> 05:01.080
confirmation or joining in an enquiry about the thing itself, not about the word, or by some other

05:01.080 --> 05:08.640
fit suggestion. 11. From Fronto I, I learned to observe what envy and duplicity and hypocrisy are

05:08.640 --> 05:13.900
in a tyrant, and that generally those among us who are called patricians are rather deficient

05:13.900 --> 05:20.600
in paternal affection. 12. From Alexander the Platonic, not frequently nor without necessity

05:20.600 --> 05:31.060
to say to anyone, or to write in a letter, that I have no leisure, nor continually to excuse the

05:31.060 --> 05:38.700
urgent occupations. 13. From Catullus, not to be indifferent when a friend finds fault, even if he

05:38.700 --> 05:44.360
should find fault without reason, but to try to restore him to his usual disposition, and to be

05:44.360 --> 05:51.920
ready to speak well of teachers, as it is reported of Demetius and Athanadotus, and to love my children truly.

05:53.760 --> 06:00.880
14. From my brother Severus, to love my kin, and to love truth, and to love justice, and through him

06:00.880 --> 06:09.080
I learned to know Thracia, Helvidius, Cato, Dion, Brutus. And from him I received the idea of a polity

06:09.080 --> 06:14.780
in which there is the same law for all, a polity administered with regard to equal rights and equal

06:14.780 --> 06:20.120
freedom of speech, and the idea of a kingly government which respects most of all the freedom

06:20.120 --> 06:26.680
of the governed. I learned from him also consistency and undeviating steadiness in my regard for

06:26.680 --> 06:32.700
philosophy, and a disposition to do good, and to give to others readily, and to cherish good hopes,

06:33.140 --> 06:38.200
and to believe that I am loved by my friends. And in him I observed no concealment of his

06:38.200 --> 06:43.120
opinions with respect to those whom he condemned, and that his friends had no need to conjecture

06:43.120 --> 06:50.820
what he wished or did not wish, but it was quite plain. 15. From Maximus I learned self-government,

06:51.100 --> 06:55.920
and not to be led aside by anything, and cheerfulness in all circumstances, as well as

06:55.920 --> 07:02.280
an illness, and a just admixture in the moral character of sweetness and dignity, and to do

07:02.280 --> 07:07.360
what was set before me without complaining. I observed that everybody believed that he thought

07:07.360 --> 07:13.660
as he spoke, and that in all that he did he never had any bad intention, and he never showed amazement

07:13.660 --> 07:19.480
and surprise, and was never in a hurry, and never put off doing a thing, nor was perplexed, nor

07:20.160 --> 07:25.220
dejected, nor did he ever laugh to disguise his vexation, nor on the other hand was he ever

07:25.220 --> 07:30.640
passionate or suspicious. He was accustomed to do acts of beneficence, and was ready to forgive,

07:31.060 --> 07:36.240
and was free from all falsehood. And he presented the appearance of a man who could not be diverted

07:36.240 --> 07:41.720
from right rather than of a man who had been improved. I observed too that no man could ever

07:41.720 --> 07:47.240
think that he was despised by Maximus, or ever ventured to think himself a better man. He had

07:47.240 --> 07:55.180
also the art of being humorous in an agreeable way. 16. In my father, I observed mildness of

07:55.180 --> 08:00.420
temper, and unchangeable resolution in the things which he had determined after due deliberation,

08:01.140 --> 08:06.600
and no vainglory in those things which men call honours, and a love of labour and perseverance,

08:07.280 --> 08:10.880
and a readiness to listen to those who had anything to propose for the common wheel,

08:11.940 --> 08:17.500
an undeviating firmness in giving to every man according to his deserts, and a knowledge

08:17.500 --> 08:23.100
derived from experience of the occasions for vigorous action and for remission. And I observed

08:23.100 --> 08:28.860
he had overcome all passion for joys, and he considered himself no more than any other citizen,

08:29.300 --> 08:34.360
and he released his friends from all obligation to sup with him or to attend him of a necessity

08:34.360 --> 08:39.800
when he went abroad. And those who failed to accompany him by reason of any urgent circumstances

08:39.800 --> 08:45.780
always found him the same. I observed too his habit of careful inquiry in all matters of

08:45.780 --> 08:51.000
deliberation, and his persistency, and that he never stopped his investigation through being

08:51.000 --> 08:56.100
satisfied with appearances which first present themselves, and that his disposition was to keep

08:56.100 --> 09:01.160
his friends and not to be soon tired of them, nor yet to be extravagant in his affection,

09:02.040 --> 09:07.860
and to be satisfied on all occasions and cheerful, and to foresee things a long way off and to

09:07.860 --> 09:13.820
provide for the smallest without display, and to check immediately popular applause and flattery,

09:13.820 --> 09:18.460
and to be ever watchful over the things which were necessary for the administration of the empire,

09:18.460 --> 09:23.600
and to be a good manager of the expenditure, and patiently to endure the blame which he got

09:23.600 --> 09:29.820
for such conduct. And he was neither superstitious with respect to the gods, nor did he court men by

09:29.820 --> 09:35.540
gifts or by trying to please them, or by flattering the populace. But he showed sobriety in all things

09:35.540 --> 09:41.940
and firmness, and never any mean thoughts or action, nor love of novelty. And the things which

09:41.940 --> 09:46.820
conduce in any way to the commodity of life, and of which fortune gives an abundant supply,

09:46.820 --> 09:52.640
he used without arrogance and without excusing himself, so that when he had them he enjoyed them

09:52.640 --> 09:58.880
without affectation, and when he had them not he did not want them. No one could ever say of him

09:58.880 --> 10:05.020
that he was either a sophist or a homebred flippant slave or patent, but everyone acknowledged him to

10:05.020 --> 10:10.900
be a man ripe, perfect, above flattery, able to manage his own and other men's affairs.

10:11.520 --> 10:16.240
Besides this he honoured those who were true philosophers, and he did not reproach those who

10:16.240 --> 10:22.180
tended to be philosophers, nor yet was he easily led by them. He was also easy in conversation,

10:22.500 --> 10:27.900
and he made himself agreeable without any offensive affectation. He took a reasonable care of his

10:27.900 --> 10:33.300
body's health, not as one who was greatly attached to life, nor out of regard to personal appearance,

10:33.800 --> 10:38.860
nor yet in a careless way, but thus so that, through his own attention, he very seldom stood

10:38.860 --> 10:45.120
in need of the physician's art or of medicine or external applications. He was most ready to give

10:45.120 --> 10:51.120
envy to those who possessed any particular faculty, such as that of eloquence or knowledge of the law

10:51.120 --> 10:56.640
or of morals or of anything else, and he gave them his help that each might enjoy reputation

10:56.640 --> 11:02.220
according to his deserts. And he always acted conformably to the institutions of his country

11:02.220 --> 11:08.500
without showing any affectation of doing so. Further, he was not fond of change nor unsteady,

11:08.820 --> 11:13.080
but he loved to stay in the same places and to employ himself about the same things,

11:13.080 --> 11:18.320
and after his paroxysms of headache he came immediately fresh and vigorous to his usual

11:18.320 --> 11:24.940
occupations. His secrets were not many, but very few and very rare, and these only about public

11:24.940 --> 11:29.740
matters, and he showed prudence and economy in the exhibition of the public spectacles

11:29.740 --> 11:34.980
and the construction of public buildings, his donations to the people, and in such things,

11:35.200 --> 11:39.380
for he was a man who looked to what ought to be done, not to the reputation which is

11:39.380 --> 11:45.480
not by a man's act. He did not take the bath at unseasonable hours. He was not fond of building

11:45.480 --> 11:51.040
houses, nor curious about what he eat, nor about the texture and colour of his clothes, nor about

11:51.040 --> 11:56.940
the beauty of his slaves. His dress came from lorium, his villa on the coast, and from linovium

11:56.940 --> 12:02.340
generally. We know how he behaved to the toll collector at Tusculum, who asked his pardon,

12:02.860 --> 12:08.920
and such was all his behaviour. There was in him nothing harsh nor implacable nor violent

12:08.920 --> 12:14.240
nor, as one may say, anything carried to the sweating point. But he examined all things

12:14.240 --> 12:19.040
severally as if he had abundance of time, and without confusion, in an orderly way,

12:19.320 --> 12:24.360
vigorously and consistently. And that might be applied to him which is recorded of Socrates,

12:24.780 --> 12:29.800
that he was able both to abstain from and to enjoy those things which many are too weak to

12:29.800 --> 12:35.520
abstain from and cannot enjoy without excess. But to be strong enough both to bear the one

12:35.520 --> 12:40.520
and to be sober in the other is the mark of a man who has a perfect and invincible soul,

12:40.960 --> 12:48.180
such as he showed in the illness of Maximus. 17. To the gods I am indebted for having good

12:48.180 --> 12:54.820
grandfathers, good parents, a good sister, good teachers, good associates, good kinsmen and

12:54.820 --> 13:00.400
friends, nearly everything good. Further, I owe it to the gods that I was not hurried into any

13:00.400 --> 13:05.420
offence against any of them, though I had a disposition which, if opportunity had offered,

13:05.720 --> 13:11.260
might have led me to do something of this kind. But, through their favour, there never was such

13:11.260 --> 13:17.120
a concurrence of circumstances as put me to the trial. Further, I am thankful to the gods that I

13:17.120 --> 13:22.060
was not longer brought up with my grandfather's concubine, and that I preserved the flower of my

13:22.060 --> 13:27.040
youth, and that I did not make proof of my virility before the proper season, but even

13:27.040 --> 13:32.240
referred to the time, that I was subjected to a ruler and a father who was able to take away all

13:32.240 --> 13:37.220
pride from me, and to bring me to the knowledge that it is possible for a man to live in a palace

13:37.220 --> 13:42.680
without wanting either guards, or embroidered dresses, or torches and statues, and such like

13:42.680 --> 13:48.200
show. But it is in such a man's power to bring himself very near to the fashion of a private

13:48.200 --> 13:53.220
person, without being for this reason either meaner in thought or more remiss in action,

13:53.220 --> 13:58.480
with respect to the things which must be done for the public interest in a manner that befits a ruler.

13:59.460 --> 14:04.260
I thank the gods for giving me such a brother who was able by his moral character to rouse me to

14:04.260 --> 14:09.700
vigilance over myself, and who, at the same time, pleased me by his respect and affection,

14:10.220 --> 14:15.780
that my children have not been stupid nor deformed in body, that I did not make more proficiency in

14:15.780 --> 14:20.580
rhetoric, poetry, and the other studies in which I should perhaps have been completely engaged

14:20.580 --> 14:25.760
if I had seen that I was making progress in them, that I made haste to place those who

14:25.760 --> 14:30.320
brought me up in the station of honor which they seemed to desire without putting them off with

14:30.320 --> 14:36.200
hope of my doing it some time after, because they were then still young, that I knew Apollonius,

14:36.440 --> 14:42.000
Rusticus, Maximus, that I received clear and frequent impressions about living according to

14:42.000 --> 14:47.820
nature, and what kind of a life that is, so that, so far as depended on the gods, and their gifts

14:47.820 --> 14:53.180
and help, and inspirations, nothing hindered me from forthwith living according to nature,

14:53.620 --> 14:58.020
though I still fall short of it through my own fault, and through not observing the admonitions

14:58.020 --> 15:04.220
of the gods, and I may almost say their direct instructions, that my body is held out so long

15:04.220 --> 15:09.660
in such a kind of life, that I never touched either Benedicta or Theodotus, and that, after

15:09.660 --> 15:15.620
having fallen into amatory passions, I was cured, and though I was often out of humor with Rusticus,

15:15.620 --> 15:20.700
I never did anything of which I had occasion to repent, that, though it was my mother's fate to

15:20.700 --> 15:26.380
die young, she spent the last years of her life with me, that, whenever I wished to help any man

15:26.380 --> 15:31.600
in his need, or in any other occasion, I was never told that I had not the means of doing it,

15:32.080 --> 15:36.260
and that to myself the same necessity never happened, to receive anything from another,

15:37.260 --> 15:42.860
that I have such a wife so obedient and so affectionate and so simple, that I had abundance

15:42.860 --> 15:47.320
of good masters for my children, and that remedies have been shown to me by dreams,

15:47.500 --> 15:52.440
both others, and against blood-spitting and giddiness, and that, when I had an inclination

15:52.440 --> 15:57.940
to philosophy, I did not fall into the hands of any sophist, and that I did not waste my time on

15:57.940 --> 16:02.940
writers of histories, or in the resolution of syllogisms, or occupy myself about the

16:02.940 --> 16:07.700
investigation of appearances in the heavens, for all these things require the help of the gods

16:07.700 --> 16:08.760
and fortune.

